iris is a terminal-based, vim-like text editor and lilac ide. it provides syntax
highlighting, code diagnostics, dependency management, source code integration,
and a whole lot more that won't matter to you until much later in your lilac
journey. for now, you need iris for one reason: to edit lilac code. to this end,
you really don't need to know much. just some basic key combinations;

[<code:list>
w: up line
s: down line
a: left character
d: right character

q: word backwards
r: word forwards

e: enter edit mode
t: enter file manager (tree).
b: enter block mode
esc: return to normal mode
]

these controls may seem weird to you now, but i promise you'll get used to them.
eventually. anyway, you need to start the iris file explorer to navigate your
project. simply type [<ref> execute iris] into your terminal and hit enter. the
file manager should immediately appear, which means you will see that file tree
that i showed in the last chapter. if you do not, make sure you created your
project and entered iris correctly, and that your lavender install is not
somehow nonstandard.

you can navigate the file explorer by moving the cursor up and down (via the w/s
keys) and hitting "enter" to select a list entry. if you select a file, you will
enter the buffer edit screen. if you select a folder, you will simply [<ref>
enter] into that directory. select [<ref> sources] and hit enter. then, select
the [<ref> entry.lilac] file. this is the entry point of your program! you
should see the following text in the buffer edit screen;

[<code:lilac>
import from std output.

entry is function; returns u32 =
{
    std/output/string; "hi world :)".
    return success.
}
]

while this syntax can be a teensy bit confusing at first, it's really quite
intuitive if you can read english. first, the import statement. this is
basically the [<ref> (#,%)include] statement in a c or nasm program. we
import the standard output module, which is a part of the [<ref> std] system
module that is integrated into lavender. you don't need to know what a "system
module" is right now, but if you develop things and have ever used an
apple-controlled os, this is one of the libraries held in the dyld cache. it
provides us with some basic routines to quickly and easily output strings,
integers (in binary, hexadecimal, and decimal formats), decimals, and a million
different other things.

next is the [<ref> entry is function] line. this just defines the identifier
[<ref> entry] as a function with no parameters that returns a 32-bit unsigned
integer. this is the default signature for the entry point function for most
applications on lavender, and the os will not pass any command-line arguments to
your process, meaning you cannot go dowsing for them in assembly like you can on
linux. we will get more into customizing the entrypoint in a couple of chapters
from now.

next is the scope of the function. everything contained between this brace and
the next brace is considered to be code belonging to the [<ref> entry] function.
this is a simple concept to understand if you've come from literally any other
programming language.

the next line contains a call to a function within the [<ref> std/output]
namespace called [<ref> string]. this function, whose signature and
documentation you will see if you hit [<key> i] in iris' normal mode, takes in a
string argument. this string will be printed to the output stream assigned to
your process, usually a running terminal.

the next statement, [<ref> return success], does exactly what it says it does.
it returns success. success is an integral value functionally equivalent to the
"true" boolean value, though it directly converts to the number 1 in decimal. we
will talk more about return values and error handling in the next couple of
chapters.

let's see if this program works! enter normal mode if you are in another mode
and then press [<key> c]. the compilation menu will open, and you should see the
following interface.

[<code:list>
compile current project.
see project compilation settings.
see project information.
]

select the "compile current project" option and hit enter. you should be treated
to a colorized output window of the compilation process. if this is the first
time you're using lavender or the lilac compiler, it may take a couple of
moments to get set up, please be patient. it should compile with a full success,
and produced should be a [<ref> product] directory with a file called
"hello_lilac" contained within it.

you can run this file by exiting pressing [<key> meta+esc] to exit iris, then
entering "execute product/hello_lilac". the output should be the string "hi
world :)" and then a report of a successful execution. note that there is a way
to execute binaries from iris, but it's meant to be used as a debugging tool and
thus the output is a little harder to navigate. we will learn how to utilize
this option later (notice all my little knowledge keys jingling in front of your
face? i have to keep you engaged somehow ;]).

and that's basically all of the skills you need to create and change a couple of
small lilac projects, like we will in these early chapters. you're doing great!

